@desc Use applications and the desktop without a mouse.

[comment]
  [cite date="2012-03-14" href="mailto:shaunm@gnome.org"]
    Shaun McCance
  Do $em(NOT) use $code(ui:expanded) on this page. I know it's
  tempting, but the target audience for this page is people who cannot use
  a mouse, and having to expand sections when you're just figuring out how
  to drive things with the keyboard is a burden.

This page details keyboard navigation for people who cannot use a mouse or
other pointing device, or who want to use a keyboard as much as possible. For
keyboard shortcuts that are useful to all users, see
$link[>shell-keyboard-shortcuts] instead.

[note .tip]
If you cannot use a pointing device like a mouse, you can control the
mouse pointer using the numeric keypad on your keyboard. See
$link[>mouse-mousekeys] for details.

[table frame="top bottom" rules="rows"]
. Navigate user interfaces
[tr]
* $key(Tab) and $keyseq($key(Ctrl)$key(Tab))
* Move keyboard focus between different controls. $keyseq($key(Ctrl)$key(Tab))
  moves between groups of controls, such as from a sidebar to the main content.
  $keyseq($key(Ctrl)$key(Tab)) can also break out of a control that uses
  $key(Tab) itself, such as a text area.

  Hold down $key(Shift) to move focus in reverse order.

[tr]
* Arrow keys
* Move selection between items in a single control, or among a set of
  related controls. Use the arrow keys to focus buttons in a toolbar, select
  items in a list or icon view, or select a radio button from a group.

[tr]
* $keyseq($key(Ctrl)Arrow keys)
* In a list or icon view, move the keyboard focus to another item
  without changing which item is selected.

[tr]
* $keyseq($key(Shift)Arrow keys)
* In a list or icon view, select all items from the currently selected
  item to the newly focused item.
* In a tree view, items that have children can be expanded or collapsed,
  to show or hide their children: expand by pressing
  $keyseq($key(Shift)$key(→)), and collapse by
  pressing $keyseq($key(Shift)$key(←)).

[tr]
* $key(Space)
* Activate a focused item such as a button, check box, or list item.

[tr]
* $keyseq($key(Ctrl)$key(Space))
* In a list or icon view, select or deselect the focused item without
  deselecting other items.

[tr]
* $key(Alt)
* Hold down the $key(Alt) key to reveal $em(accelerators):
  underlined letters on menu items, buttons, and other controls. Press
  $key(Alt) plus the underlined letter to activate a control, just
  as if you had clicked on it.

[tr]
* $key(Esc)
* Exit a menu, popup, switcher, or dialog window.

[tr]
* $key(F10)
* Open the first menu on the menubar of a window. Use the arrow keys
  to navigate the menus.

[tr]
* $keyseq($key(Super)$key(F10))
* Open the application menu on the top bar.

[tr]
* $keyseq($key(Shift)$key(F10)) or $key(Menu)
* Pop up the context menu for the current selection, as if you had
  right-clicked.

[tr]
* $keyseq($key(Ctrl)$key(F10))
* In the file manager, pop up the context menu for the current folder,
  as if you had right-clicked on the background and not on any item.

[tr]
* $keyseq($key(Ctrl)$key(PageUp)) and $keyseq($key(Ctrl)$key(PageDown))
* In a tabbed interface, switch to the tab to the left or right.

